  1. This mini-project is open-ended, and while working on it, there might be some situations where you'll have to use your own judgment and make your own decisions (as you would be doing when you work as a data scientist). Make sure you explain your decisions whenever necessary.
  2. Do not include everything you ever tried in your submission -- it's fine just to have your final code. That said, your code should be reproducible and well-documented. For example, if you chose your hyperparameters based on some hyperparameter optimization experiment, you should leave in the code for that experiment so that someone else could re-run it and obtain the same hyperparameters, rather than mysteriously just setting the hyperparameters to some (carefully chosen) values in your code.

1. Pick your problem and explain the prediction problem ¶

rubric={points:3}

In this mini project, you have the option to choose on which dataset you will be working on. The tasks you will need to carry on will be similar, independently of your choice.

Option 1¶

You can choose to work on a classification problem of predicting whether a credit card client will default or not. For this problem, you will use Default of Credit Card Clients Dataset. In this data set, there are 30,000 examples and 24 features, and the goal is to estimate whether a person will default (fail to pay) their credit card bills; this column is labeled "default.payment.next.month" in the data. The rest of the columns can be used as features. You may take some ideas and compare your results with the associated research paper, which is available through the UBC library.

Option 2¶

You can choose to work on a regression problem using a dataset of New York City Airbnb listings from 2019. As usual, you'll need to start by downloading the dataset, then you will try to predict reviews_per_month, as a proxy for the popularity of the listing. Airbnb could use this sort of model to predict how popular future listings might be before they are posted, perhaps to help guide hosts create more appealing listings. In reality they might instead use something like vacancy rate or average rating as their target, but we do not have that available here.

Note there is an updated version of this dataset with more features available here. The features were are using in listings.csv.gz for the New York city datasets. You will also see some other files like reviews.csv.gz. For your own interest you may want to explore the expanded dataset and try your analysis there. However, please submit your results on the dataset obtained from Kaggle.

I would like to pick the default of credit card clients dataset, to work on the classification problem of predicting whether a credit card client will default or not.

There are 30,000 examples and 24 features in the dataset, plus the target column called default.payment.next.month. The features offering in the dataset include the amount of given credit, education level, marital status, age, repayment status from April to September, amount of bill statement from April to September, and the amount of previous payment from April to September. Many of them are ordinal variables, and some are numerical. Based on my preliminary considerations, all of them are helpful for our predition for the default behaviors, I may only exclude the sex column due to the lack of biological relevance in our goal and the ethical and fairness concerns.

Here we see the data imbalance in our dataset: much more non-default clients than the default ones.

Our task is predicting whether a client will default or not. In the credit card repayment background, we would pay more attention to the default clients, so successfully identifying a client will default is more important than finding the one who will not default.

Therefore I will prioritize F1-score to ranking different models. In the following model evaluation part, I will use f1-score instead of accuracy.

Summary

I find there are no text data in the dataset, and there are some numerical features, ordinal features, binary features in the dataset. We will need to scaling the numeric features such as LIMIT_BAL. I will drop SEX column since I do not find there are siginificant roles of it in our prediction. For ordinal features such as MARRIAGE and EDUCATION, there are some values that doesn't provide any valid information, such as "other" and "unknown", and even undocumented values, I will treat them as the missing values and replace them with NA. There could be appropriate interaction between some of the numeric features such as PAY_AMT* and LIMIT_BAL. I also notice that there is data imbalance with much more samples of non-default clients, but our prediction task stress more on identifying the default clients, so I will use F1 score as my model evaluation score instead of accuracy score.

from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin
class ReplaceValues(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, replace_dict):
        self.replace_dict = replace_dict
        
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self
    
    def transform(self, X):
        return X.replace(self.replace_dict)
# reference: https://towardsdatascience.com/customizing-scikit-learn-pipelines-write-your-own-transformer-fdaaefc5e5d7

# Create instances of transformers

# reference: hw3
results_dict = {}

def mean_std_cross_val_scores(model, X_train, y_train, **kwargs):
    """
    Returns mean and std of cross validation

    Parameters
    ----------
    model :
        scikit-learn model
    X_train : numpy array or pandas DataFrame
        X in the training data
    y_train :
        y in the training data

    Returns
    ----------
        pandas Series with mean scores from cross_validation
    """

    scores = cross_validate(model, X_train, y_train, **kwargs, scoring="f1")

    mean_scores = pd.DataFrame(scores).mean()
    std_scores = pd.DataFrame(scores).std()
    out_col = []

    for i in range(len(mean_scores)):
        out_col.append((f"%0.3f (+/- %0.3f)" % (mean_scores.iloc[i], std_scores.iloc[i])))

    return pd.Series(data=out_col, index=mean_scores.index)

# reference: lecture 08
best_score = 0

param_grid = {
    "C": [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100],
    'max_iter': [500, 1000, 1500],
}

results_dict_hyperpara = {"C": [], "max_iter": [], "mean_cv_score": []}

for max_iter in param_grid["max_iter"]:
    for C in param_grid["C"]:  # for each combination of parameters, train an SVC
        pipe_lr = make_pipeline(preprocessor, LogisticRegression(max_iter=max_iter, C=C))
        scores = cross_val_score(pipe_lr, X_train, y_train, scoring='f1')  # perform cross-validation
        mean_score = np.mean(scores)  # compute mean cross-validation accuracy
        if (
            mean_score > best_score
        ):  # if we got a better score, store the score and parameters
            best_score = mean_score
            best_parameters = {"C": C, "max_iter": max_iter}
        results_dict_hyperpara["C"].append(C)
        results_dict_hyperpara["max_iter"].append(max_iter)
        results_dict_hyperpara["mean_cv_score"].append(mean_score)

The credit default prediction problem revealed the performance of different machine learning models. The Random Forest model outperformed others like k-NN classifier, svm rbf, and logistical regression with an F1-score of 0.447（0.459 after hyperparameter tuning, 0.4633 on test data）and an AUC of 0.7551, indicating its robustness in identifying clients as potential defaulters.

My model here has a slightly higher final test score than its mean validation score. This could be luck, but with its low standard deviation of 0.010 in the validation scores, I would say the results would be reliable to be applied on the future unseen data.

The model's feature importance analysis highlighted key predictors, such as payment amounts and limit balances, which are crucial for decision-making in credit assessment.

Other ideas:

  1. I am considering creating a new feature called repayment rate by deviding the payment amount in each month by the amount of bill statement in each month, and I think there may be strong relationship between the repayment rate in each month and the default behavior, which could help us to make prediction. However, creating this new column needs us to drop the original columns used to calculate it in order to avoid multicollinearity, but the feature importance section has shown us that the PAY_AMT1 column contributes a lot to our prediction, and the interaction between LIMIT_BILL and BILL_AMT* follows up. If we just drop the columns, our model performance might work worse. This would need further comparison in different models, which might perform better than my final model here.

  2. I must acknowledge that in the process of training and selecting different models, I reduced some values of some hyperparameters such as the number of folds for cross-validation and the value of n_estimator= argument, just to save time. If there is a higher time budget, there might be a better perforance from a better model. For sure, a faster performance itself never be bad.

My final random forest model has an f1-score of 0.463338.
